<TEXT>
more than 7 million in proceeds from the sale of 
foreclosed homes may be missing from the department of housing and 
urban and developments regional office here federal auditors say 
however huds regional chief said the files that will account 
for the money are simply in storage and are being recovered 
the denver hud office is a major focus of a nationwide inquiry of 
wrongdoing at hud during the reagan administration under 
thensecretary samuel pierce 
the agency has been rocked by allegations that money to 
rehabilitate rundown housing for the poor and elderly was handed 
out to developers who hired highpriced consultants with ties to the 
republican party or the administration 
in addition an escrow agent in maryland has said she embezzled 
5 million in money due the government from the sale of foreclosed 
property and gave most of the proceeds to the poor investigators 
have dubbed mary louise harrell robin hud 
an auditors report released tuesday raised the possibility that 
the denver office may not have received 7279136 
federal auditors have given the office eight days to come up with 
the missing records on 173 foreclosed homes sold in the past five 
years or face sanctions 
hud regional officials knew the files were missing as early as 
feb 9 according to the report by the hud inspector generals 
office the report indicates the investigation into singlefamily 
home sales handled by the office began in january 
the report said 471 home sales were chosen by auditors for 
review but records on 173 couldnt be found 
according to the report documentation that proceeds were 
transferred to hud bank accounts was lacking for many other sales 
isaiah ike kelley acting hud administrator in denver said 
the files which have been missing since february are stored in 
agencys archives 
kelley said the audit covered home sales from 1984 to 1988 
i dont know what happened back then but i can tell you that 
as acting administrator i will make sure the regional inspector 
general obtains those files immediately said kelley who took 
over in april 
earlier this month a hud accountant in denver douglas turner 
was suspended on suspicion of diverting 1 million to his own 
account 
the auditors report accused regional officials of lax 
recordkeeping 
auditors complained they found active and inactive files together 
and that boxes of records were allowed to sit open at the regional 
office for indefinite periods before being put in storage 
the report also criticized the practice of not requiring private 
agents who sell foreclosed properties for hud to confirm that 
proceeds were deposited in hud bank accounts normally when a hud 
home is sold the proceeds are wired immediately to the agencys 
washington office 
of the 256 sales packages examined 145 did not have wire 
transfer confirmations the report said 
