<TEXT>
two black candidates won races for 
judgeships tuesday in an election ordered by a federal judge who 
said mississippis judicial districts discriminated against blacks 
one other black candidate was narrowly leading one was trailing 
and two others lost election bids two blacks were unopposed as a 
result of the court order that forced the redrawing of judicial 
districts prior to the election mississippi had four black judges 
also on the ballot were three proposed constitutional amendments 
to repeal outdated and unused provisions one would eliminate the 
poll tax adopted to discourage black voting but struck down by the 
us supreme court in 1966 
the four blacks among mississippis 78 judges are supreme court 
justice reuben anderson circuit judges fred l banks jr and lillie 
blackmonsanders and chancery judge isaac byrd 
each was appointed to fill a vacancy but anderson went on to win 
a full eightyear term in 1986 byrd did not seek election this 
year the two others sought regular terms tuesday 
with 79 of 85 precincts reporting tuesday night blackmonsanders 
trailed republican challenger richard watson by 8265 votes to 
10917 banks and one other black democrat isadore w patrick of 
vicksburg were unopposed in the general election 
the two black winners were pat wise a democrat who defeated 
republican billy w keyes for an open hinds county chancery judges 
post by 5942 votes to 1638 and denise sweet owens also democrat 
who defeated republican george m arthur in another open family 
court post in the county 4628 votes to 1259 
with only five of 37 precincts reporting in the fourth district 
solomon curtis osborne a black democrat was leading independent 
incumbent circuit judge gray evans in the fourth district 395 votes 
to 348 
but clell g ward a black democrat was defeated by independent 
incumbent circuit judge howard q davis jr in the fourth district 
4046 votes to 2063 
another black candidate harold brittain also a democrat ran 
fourth in a fourway race for two judgeship posts in the 20 circuit 
court district the winners were incumbents robert l goza a 
democrat and alfred nichols a republican 
in 1987 us district judge william h barbour jr ruled that 
the states judicial districts discriminated against blacks the 
ruling the first to apply the 1965 voting rights act to judicial 
elections was upheld on appeal 
barbour ordered some districts redrawn to create minority 
subdistricts so that black voters would have a better opportunity to 
elect black judges 
the ruling and appeals put judicial elections in the state on 
hold until this year when all 69 circuit court and chancery court 
judgeships are being filled no supreme court judgeships are on the 
ballot 
