<TEXT>
the senate foreign relations committee 
postponed action on three of president bushs ambassadorial nominees 
tuesday after democrats complained their only visible qualifications 
are large gop contributions 
sen paul sarbanes dmd initiated the delay when he complained 
that us ambassadors should have at least some qualifications for 
the job 
the senate is set to close down for the independence day recess 
so sarbanes request for a oneweek delay effectively stops until 
mid july at the earliest any action on the nominations to fill 
ambassadorships in spain australia and new zealand 
in the past weve had to hold our noses and let similar 
nominees with political connections go through sarbanes said but 
eventually someone ought to say stop 
if its going to be a bidding war at least we should put it 
up for public bids so the money goes to the us treasury 
sarbanes said 
sarbanes targeted three they are 
joseph zappala a florida land developer and national 
cochairman of bushs fund raising committee who has been nominated 
to be us ambassador to spain sarbanes said he contributed 
126000 to the bush campaign 
marvin sembler a florida shopping center tycoon who has been 
named to be ambassador to australia sarbanes said sembler was a 
127000 bush contributor 
della newman a seattle wash residential real estate broker 
who has been nominated to be ambassador to new zealand she is a 
longtime personal friend of bush and was chairman of the washington 
state bush for president committee sarbanes said she had no 
apparent qualifications except her personal and political ties 
there seems to be a 100000 threshhold for ambassadorships 
sarbanes said 
sarbanes did reluctantly permit the committee to approve the 
nomination of c howard wilkins jr a 115000 contributor to the 
bush campaign wilkins has been named to be ambassador to the 
netherlands and with the committees action an ambassador will be 
in place when bush visits the country next month 
the full senate later approved the wilkins nomination on a voice 
vote 
sen connie mack rfla defended the records of the two 
floridians on sarbanes list saying to imply they are not capable 
is a disservice 
sen frank murkowski ralaska said what were doing is 
delaying the appropriate representation this country should have 
overseas 
and sen richard lugar rind said the overall composition of 
bushs ambassadorial nominees to date is no different than the 
choices of the reagan administrations twothirds foreign service 
professionals and one third political appointees 
these nominees are friends of the president a part of the 
organization of his coming to the presidency lugar said they 
share his ethos his idealism and they will be so perceived in the 
nations to which they are being sent 
sarbanes said he has no objection to political nominees as such 
as long as they can claim some qualifications for the posts to which 
they are named he noted he did not object to bushs nomination of 
former republican gov robert d orr of indiana to be ambassador to 
singapore 
he said orr had demonstrated his capabilities during his eight 
years service as governor beginning in 1980 
the committee did vote to recommend the senate confirm orr and a 
list of other nominees 
they are 
thomas niles named to be us representative to the european 
community 
morton i abramowitz to be ambassador to turkey 
edward n ney to be ambassador to canada 
richard h solomon to be assistant secretary of state for east 
asian and pacific affairs 
melvyn levitsky to be assistant secretary of state for 
international narcotics matters 
jewel s lafontant to be ambassadoratlarge for refugee 
affairs 
e patrick coady to be us executive director for the 
international bank for reconstruction and development 
mark l edelman to be deputy administrator of the agency for 
international development 
fred m zeder ii to be president of the overseas private 
investment corp 
