<TEXT>
authorities took extra precautions against 
potential sabotage by workers at the rancho seco nuclear power 
station near sacramento calif after city residents voted to close 
the troubled plant officials disclosed 
the only incident since the june 6 vote was resolved safely but 
federal regulators said tuesday theyre keeping a close eye on plant 
conditions as the sacramento municipal utility district gradually 
switches off the reactor with a shrinking work force 
its not what youd call an unsafe situation but the unusual 
circumstances of the plant shutdown have prompted extra caution 
said thomas murley director of the nuclear regulatory commissions 
office of reactor regulation 
the vote marked the first time citizens have decided to close an 
operating reactor but analysts say it seems unlikely the move will 
trigger other closures soon still the shutdown is a blow to an 
industry already hampered by widespread public concerns about the 
safety and reliability of nuclear power 
rancho seco has a spotty record producing less than 40 percent 
of the electricity that would have resulted from unfailing 
yearround operation far below the industry average the utility 
district had to double its rates over the past four years to pay for 
plant improvements that cost more than the reactor itself 
murley said plant executives gave him explicit assurances that 
the shutdown would go smoothly and he said that so far there was no 
evidence to the contrary 
its a very tough period because all the good people will be 
looking for other jobs murley said adding that there also was a 
danger of bad reactions by plant workers to being forced out of 
the 15yearold nuclear station 
the utility districts senior nuclear executive joseph firlit 
has resigned and about 1000 regular plant workers were expected to 
leave by months end 
the nrc which is responsible for ensuring safety at the nations 
110 nuclear reactors boosted its usual complement of three resident 
inspectors at rancho seco by three or four for several days before 
and after the election greg cook a spokesman at the commisions 
regional office in walnut creek calif said tuesday 
cook said extra security inspectors also were sent to the site to 
provide aroundtheclock surveillance the nrc has returned to 
normal levels of supervision at the plant he said 
the utility increased its security at the site but has since 
trimmed it back said spokesman bert heffner he said he was not 
sure of all the reasons for the added protection but that a rush of 
news reporters to the plant was one 
edward smeloff a member of the utility districts board said in 
an interview that utility security personnel were added as a general 
precaution against possible worker backlash and because of a a 
specific incident with one disgruntled employee 
an offduty reactor operator angered at the prospect of losing 
his job telephoned the plant the day after the election to say he 
would not shut it down if so ordered said smeloff 
heffner said the incident did not constitute a threat to 
security but the workers access to the plant was suspended he 
said no decision has been made on possible disciplinary action 
against the man whose name was not disclosed 
dean kunihiro an official at the nrcs walnut creek office said 
that while its kind of business as usual again at rancho seco 
the commission is still watchful because a serious accident 
involving radioactive release is still possible even though the 
reactor is no longer sustaining a chain reaction 
the plant owner is planning to remove the fuel rods from the 
reactor vessel in august but has not yet decided whether it will 
continue with the lengthy process of dismantling the plant or try to 
sell it to another potential operator 
