<TEXT>
the us justice department has sued a suburb for 
denying a zoning permit for a home for retarded adults 
the lawsuit filed tuesday was the first brought by the federal 
government alleging housing discrimination against the handicapped 
under the fair housig amendments act that went into effect march 12 
the department said 
the department contends the chicago heights city council denied 
the request in may because of neighbors opposition based on fears 
and prejudices concerning the mentally retarded 
the council in the suburb of 32000 people denied a specialuse 
permit for construction of a home for 15 adults in a neighborhood of 
singlefamily and twofamily homes 
chicago heights police commissioner john gliottoni one of the 
five council members said the council followed recommendations of 
the citys zoning board and its planning commission as it almost 
always does 
they are the sounding boards gliottoni said they listen 
to all the people who are for it and all the people who are against 
it we as council members have no input whatsoever 
james p turner acting assistant attorney general in charge of 
the justice departments civil rights division said the case 
signals our determination to make sure that the handicapped enjoy 
the full benefits of the protections the act gives them 
under the new fair housing act stereotypes and baseless fears 
concerning the handicapped cannot be used to block the development 
of group homes turner said in the statement from washington 
the lawsuit asks the federal court in chicago to bar chicago 
heights from interfering with construction of the home and to assess 
unspecified damages and a penalty 
turner defended the concept of group homes which have 
encountered opposition from prospective neighbors and delaying 
tactics around the country 
studies have shown that these facilities are better for 
residents than the outofsight outofmind institutions of the 
past and that they have no adverse effects on the neighborhood 
he said 
