<TEXT>
charter planes flew hundreds of weary 
tourists home today after they were plucked from a soviet ocean 
liner that had crashed into an iceberg cutting short a pleasure 
cruise to the land of the midnight sun 
workers plugged the holes on the 630foot cruise ship maxim gorky 
and the vessel steamed toward the island of spitsbergen today 
escorted by two other soviet vessels the soviet news agency tass 
said 
maritime experts said the ocean liner on a cruise to see the 
24hour summer light in the arctic was moving too fast when it 
struck the ice in the norwegian sea 300 miles east of northern 
greenland and 180 miles west of spitsbergen no one was seriously 
injured 
norwegian helicopters flew the aged and most infirm to safety 
but some passengers spent up to seven hours huddled under blankets 
in lifeboats until they were picked up others waited on ice floes 
for west german passenger giesela rillinger it was six hours 
of nothing but ice floes and the sky if a storm had come up it 
would have been all over for us six hours of facing death 
the norwegian coast guard ship senja evacuated 660 passengers 
all but about a dozen west germans and 193 maxim gorky crew 
members to longyearbyen norways administrative center on 
spitzbergen island from where the tourists were flown to 
dusseldorf west germany 
capt marat s galimov and 192 other soviet crew members remained 
on the maxim gorky said sigurd kleiven captain of the senja 
kleiven said it was galimovs first voyage in the area 
tour leader winfried prinz said he was standing on the bridge 
next to galimov when the ship struck the iceberg 
it happened very fast prinz told a reporter in dusseldorf 
we went into the ice field without warning and unexpectedly 
something nobody had counted on the ship was cruising at normal 
speed about 18 knots so it wasnt exactly slow as the collision 
shook the ship prinz said 
kleiven said the liner was moving at 184 knots when it hit the 
ice tearing a gash 20 feet long and four to six inches wide in the 
bow 
i would hardly have sailed faster than two to three knots in 
such iceclogged water kleiven told reporters on board his coast 
guard vessel 
there was fog in the area and it seems to me as if the maxim 
gorky may have sped too fast straight into the ice kleiven said 
but experienced norwegian sailors agreed the maxim gorky had 
sailed too fast in an area often clogged with ice 
not even the coast guard vessels sail faster than three to five 
knots in such waters guttorm jacobsen a skipper who has sailed 
the arctic for 40 years told the verdens gang newspaper the 
maxim gorky must have been too eager to keep its schedule 
the newspaper quoted other experts as saying that even if the 
captain had seen the ice from a distance of 10 miles it would have 
taken his ship up to 45 minutes to stop from a speed of 18 knots 
the soviet embassy in oslo said the ship today was moving at 45 
knots toward spitzbergen where it would receive emergency repairs 
it was accompanied by a soviet tugboat and a freighter 
the ship set out june 11 from bremerhaven west germany sailed 
to iceland and encountered its difficulties while sailing around the 
spitsbergen archipelago on its way to norway 
maxim gorky had about 952 people aboard when it struck the ice 
early tuesday while most passengers were partying in a shipboard 
nightclub 
the luxury liner was built in 1969 in west germany and sold to 
the soviets in 1974 
