<TEXT>
florida lawmakers passed a bill making 
gun owners subject to prison terms if their firearms are used by 
children to shoot someone 
the legislature acted after accidental shootings killed three 
children since june 5 
we have experienced too many tragedies and its time to put an 
end to them said rep harry jennings a retired army colonel who 
has pushed the proposal for two years 
the senate passed the gunsafety bill 266 and the house approved 
it 7139 on tuesday gov bob martinez who was persuaded last week 
to include the bill in this weeks special session was expected to 
sign the measure 
under the bill gun owners who fail to secure loaded weapons in 
their homes could be charged with a felony carrying up to five years 
in prison and a 5000 fine if children 15 years and younger hurt 
someone with the firearms 
if the child displays the gun in public the gun owner could be 
charged with a misdemeanor punishable by up to 60 days in jail and a 
500 fine 
exemptions are provided for hunting and target shooting 
accidents shootings involving stolen guns and the guns of law 
enforcement officers or military personnel the law also provides a 
sevenday delay before parents of a wounded child can be arrested on 
the felony charge 
jennings the bills sponsor described it as one of the most 
important pieces of legislation that we have addressed in years in 
this legislature 
his legislation gained national attention after three florida 
children were killed and four wounded in seven accidents earlier 
this month 
the bill requires gunshop owners to post a sign explaining the 
law and to hand out a written warning to customers the measure also 
directs the state department of education to prepare a gunsafety 
education program that lawmakers can consider next year 
a lobbyist for the national rifle association said the bill was 
acceptable 
my job was to try to help produce a bill that had the potential 
to do some good and not just run willynilly damaging additional 
lives said nra lobbyist marion hammer 
rep dick locke led the opponents in the house which had 
approved a similar version during the regular session that ended 
june 3 
this bill does not make common sense locke said you cant 
put mama and daddy in jail the kids in a foster home the court 
system is full the fails are full 
other opponents contended that more children are hurt and killed 
in accidents involving cars pools fires and household poisons than 
guns 
accidental gunshots are the fifthleading cause of death of us 
children under age 14 and florida has one of the three highest 
rates of accidental shootings in the country according to sen 
jeanne malchon who proposed similar legislation two years ago 
last year 441 florida children were injured or killed by guns 
and another 3110 were victims of crimes involving firearms 
</TEXT>
