<TEXT>
an anticipated supreme court showdown over 
state child pornography laws fizzled today when the justices in 
splintered voting sent a massachusetts case back to that states 
courts 
the court told the massachusetts supreme judicial court to decide 
whether a sinceamended state law can be used to prosecute douglas 
oakes 40 of holden mass for soliciting a child to pose in 
a state of nudity for pornographic purposes 
todays ruling is a setback for oakes who had been freed from 
any criminal liability by the states highest court 
oakes was criminally convicted in worcester county prosecutors 
said that in 1984 he induced his 14yearold stepdaughter to pose 
for photographs while clothed only in bikini underpants and a scarf 
police were contacted after the girls mother discovered the 
photos 
oakes was sentenced to 10 years in prison and was paroled after 
two years 
the states highest court threw out oakes conviction and 
dismissed the criminal indictment against him the state court said 
the 1982 law under which oakes was prosecuted was too broad and 
criminalized conduct that virtually every person would regard as 
lawful 
for example the state court said in its ruling the law 
makes a criminal of a parent who takes a frontal view picture of his 
or her naked 1yearold running on a beach or romping in a wading 
pool 
the law later was amended to add a lascivious intent 
requirement 
todays decision was accompanied by three written opinions but no 
majority opinion attracting at least five justices 
four of the courts members led by justice sandra day oconnor 
said the issue of whether the original massachusetts law was 
overbroad became moot when it was amended 
two justices antonin scalia and harry a blackmun voted to 
reverse the massachusetts court and rule that oakes prosecution was 
constitutional 
perhaps i am wrong in my estimation of how frequently the 
posings prohibited by the old law are done for artistic purposes 
or for family photographs or in some other legitimate and 
constitutionally protected context i have not envisioned scalia 
wrote in an opinion joined by blackmun 
we can deal with such a situation in the unlikely event some 
prosecutor brings an indictment he said 
three justices william j brennan thurgood marshall and john 
paul stevens said the court should uphold the state court decision 
and rule that the original childporn law violated freespeech 
rights 
writing for the three brennan noted that the american sunbathing 
association a nudist group told the court that photographs taken 
of its 30000 members in the united states and canada could lead to 
prosecutions under the old massachusetts law 
the case is massachusetts vs oakes 871651 
