<TEXT>
suburban chicago heights violated an 
antidiscrimination law when its city council blocked construction 
of a home for mentally retarded adults the us justice department 
alleges in a lawsuit 
it is the first lawsuit brought by the department alleging 
housing discrimination against the handicapped under the fair 
housing amendments act that took effect march 12 the agency said in 
a news release 
at issue is a may 1 vote by the city council in the southern 
suburb of 32000 people denying a specialuse permit for 
construction of a home for 15 mentally retarded adults in a 
neighborhood of singlefamily and twofamily homes the department 
said 
the complaint filed tuesday in federal court in chicago 
contends the council denied the request because of neighbors 
opposition based on fears and prejudices the statement said 
under the new fair housing act stereotypes and baseless fears 
concerning the handicapped cannot be used to block the development 
of group homes said james p turner acting assistant attorney 
general in charge of of the civil rights division in the statement 
issued in washington 
studies have shown that these facilities are better for 
residents than the outofsight outofmind institutions of the 
past and that they have no adverse effects on the neighborhood 
turner said 
james creswell corporation counsel for chicago heights did not 
immediately return a telephone call seeking comment on the lawsuit 
chicago heights police commissioner john gliottoni one of the 
five council members would not comment on the merits of the case 
because of the lawsuit 
but he said the council followed the lead of the citys zoning 
board and its plan commission in the decision 
they are the sounding boards gliottoni said of the two 
panels they listen to all the people who are for it and all the 
people who are against it we as council members have no input 
whatsoever 
he said both groups denied zoning approval and the council 
followed those recommendations as it does more than 99 percent of 
the time 
the justice department statement said the building permit was 
sought by rfms inc a galesburg company that specializes in 
developing homes for the retarded there was no answer at a 
telephone number listed for rfms 
