<TEXT>
a medicine commonly used to control epilepsy in 
pregnant women appears to cause minor birth defects and retardation 
raising a dilemma about how to prevent seizures that can also harm 
the unborn a study concludes 
other epilepsy drugs have already been linked with birth defects 
now researchers say that one called tegretol or carbamazepine should 
be added to the list 
the drugs manufacturer questioned the way the study was 
conducted and its conclusion 
physicians who treat women with seizures are in a very 
difficult position said ronald v lacro a coauthor of the 
study this is the drug of choice because it seemed to be safe we 
cant say that anymore 
the study found evidence that women who took tegretol during 
pregnancy were more likely to produce babies with delayed 
development and mental retardation they were also more likely to 
have unusual facial formations including upward slanting eyes 
long upper lips and short noses and incomplete development of the 
fingernails 
cibageigy the company that makes tegretol said the latest 
study is a reminder that the risks and benefits of anticonvulsant 
drugs need to be weighed carefully but that the medicine should 
still be considered for epileptic women who want to have children 
we feel that our past data show that tegretol is a good option 
for epileptic women we still feel that way said spokeswoman 
cathy kernen 
the study was directed by dr kenneth lyons jones of the 
university of californiasan diego it was published in thursdays 
new england journal of medicine 
studies have found that severe epileptic seizures during 
pregnancy can temporarily interrupt the flow of blood to the fetus 
causing brain damage however epileptic women have an increased 
risk of producing babies with minor birth defects even if they 
dont have seizures during their pregnancies 
counseling has to start before pregnancy for these women 
said lacro a pediatrician at childrens hospital in boston if 
the woman has severe enough seizures and needs the medicine then by 
all means you have to give it but there is no completely safe 
therapy other than being off medications 
the researchers first identified the pattern of birth defects in 
eight children who had been exposed to the drug before birth they 
confirmed it by evaluating an additional 48 children whose mothers 
had taken the medicine 
they found that 11 percent of those exposed had facial 
abnormalities 26 percent had incomplete finger nails and 20 percent 
were slow to develop 
only one of the youngsters with delayed development was old 
enough to take an intelligence test that child aged 6 had an iq 
of 65 
in a statement cibageigy criticized the study for serious 
methodological problems it noted that the doctors used women who 
did not have epilepsy in a comparison group the higher risk of 
birth defects among the children of the epileptic women might have 
resulted from the epilepsy not the medications it said 
lacro said i think that what we are seeing is due to the drug 
if the changes that we saw were due to seizures alone then we would 
see the same pattern of malformations for all kinds of seizure 
drugs i think the defects are drug specific but i cant prove 
that 
</TEXT>
