the bush administration on wednesday raised the 
prospect that a childcare package being pushed by the senates 
democratic leadership would be vetoed and republicans sought support 
for an alternative the white house supports 
the specter of a veto was raised in an administration policy 
statement distributed on capitol hill as the senate debated the 
issue for a fifth day at the white house however a spokesman said 
president bush still hoped to reach agreement with congress on a 
plan 
in the threepage policy statement the administration said the 
childcare package being advocated by democratic leaders with the 
help of one leading gop senator orrin hatch of utah is 
fundamentally flawed and that if it reached the white house bushs 
senior advisers would recommend that he veto it 
bush spokesman marlin fitzwater was less direct when asked 
whether bush would veto the legislation if it clears congress as it 
stands now 
fitzwater said the administration believed its tax credit 
proposal was the best approach to helping lowincome parents pay for 
child care but was willing to talk about alternatives and how this 
could be approved 
the legislation before the senate is a revised version of the act 
for better child care sponsored by hatch and sen christopher dodd 
dconn it authorizes 175 billion to be spent on child care in 
fiscal 1990 through subsidies to parents and states to help pay for 
child care and expand its availability 
states would be required to give 70 percent of the money directly 
to lowincome families for child care expenses with the rest used 
to fund and administer state programs designed to improve the 
quality and quantity of child care 
tacked on to the measure is a package of tax credits designed to 
help parents offset the costs of child care and health insurance 
those credits endorsed by the senate finance committee are similar 
to the credits at the heart of the alternative package being offered 
by senate republican leader bob dole of kansas with the support of 
the white house 
but dole and other gop lawmakers have virtually ignored the 
taxcredit provisions of the revised doddhatch plan and focused 
their attacks on the subsidy provisions of the measure which they 
contend give too much control of the money to state governments and 
not enough to parents 
the alternative republican plan includes an expansion of the 
existing earnedincome tax credit for parents with children under 
age 5 and a proposal to provide money up front to lowincome 
families who cannot take advantage of the dependentcare credit 
because their incomes are so low they do not pay taxes 
the senate is scheduled to vote thursday on whether to kill the 
democratic leadership plan in favor of the gop approach 
republicans have been lobbying southern democrats in hope of 
winning enough support for their package but the democratic 
leadership says it has the votes to quash the gop effort 
