<TEXT>
the nation soon may face a shortage of 
electricity a senior energy department official said wednesday in 
comments reflecting a bush administration campaign to convince the 
public of a need for more nuclear power plants 
the demand for electricity in the united states is growing 
beyond our ability to provide additional generating capacity said 
john c tuck the undersecretary of energy 
he noted that electricity accounts for 37 percent of total us 
energy use 
tuck said it was inescapable that many more power plants will 
be needed if the economy is to continue to grow at a reasonable 
rate adding that utilities have balked at such construction because 
of the high cost and lack of public support no new nuclear plants 
have been ordered in the united states since 1978 
considering all these factors it is apparent that the nation 
may have an electricity shortage on its hands in the nottoodistant 
future tuck said in remarks to an industrysponsored symposium on 
nuclear reactors and us energy security 
tuck cited the case of long islands shoreham nuclear power 
station which new york state is planning to dismantle even though 
it recently gained a license to operate the energy department is 
trying to block the move arguing that shoreham is needed as a 
regional energy source and a national symbol of nuclear powers 
future 
tuck said the energy department is eager to complete research and 
development on several new types of nuclear reactors designed to be 
safer and more reliable than the lightwater reactors that have been 
used in this country since the 1950s 
we at the energy department believe that nuclear energy led by 
a new generation of advanced reactors will have a role in averting 
a possible electricity shortage he said 
tuck said a greater reliance on nuclear power also would help 
limit the nations dependence on foreign oil although this is 
disputed by many private analysts they note that while nuclear 
powers only nonmilitary role is to generate electricity oilfired 
plant produce only about 5 percent of the nations electricity 
about twothirds of the oil is used in cars and other vehicles 
nuclear power plants generate about 20 percent of the electricity 
supply 
