president carlos andres perez on 
wednesday told delegations from 127 nations that the economic 
totalitarianism of the developed world is crushing an increasingly 
restive third world 
perez in a welcoming speech to the un group of 77 praised the 
us brady plan as an important initiative for relieving the burden 
of a 13 trillion debt on the third world 
but we impatiently wait for the concrete gains in light of 
our urgent situation said perez 
perezs efforts to impose austerity measures in his country 
backed by international creditors prompted riots in february that 
killed about 300 people 
similar riots were reported in may in argentina another large 
contributor to latin americas 401 billion foreign debt 
perez said 40 countries in the underdeveloped world with a 
combined population of more than 800 million faced severe 
financial problems because of the debt he said that since 1982 
those countries signed up to 90 restructuring agreements with banks 
but the banks never agreed to interest rates at or below market 
rates 
when we speak of that economic totalitarianism that is forced 
on us we refer to insensitive attempts to relegate our economic 
and social development to immediate needs of fiscal balance in order 
to assure the payment of the debt perez said 
the plan proposed by us treasury secretary nicholas brady on 
march 10 encourages banks to forgive a substantial portion of their 
loans to heavily indebted countries in return for guarantees that 
the rest will be paid the international monetary fund and the world 
bank would furnish the guarantees 
the brady plan also calls for economic reforms in debtor 
countries in order to receive the benefits of reductions in the debt 
perez said developed countries call for belttightening for the 
poor when they lived beyond their means at the expense of the rest 
of the world 
he castigated the industrialized nations for basing their growth 
on the destruction of the environment along with an immoral export 
of toxic wastes to the third world 
perez made calls to the group of 77 to renew the commitment to 
economic cooperation within the underdeveloped world saying such 
efforts had flagged under the strain of the debt crisis 
the group a nonaligned organization within the un system was 
formed 25 years ago to give underdeveloped nations a forum to push 
for changes in the international economy 
originally comprised of 77 member nations the group officially 
admitted mongolia as its 128th member wednesday 
the group meeting until friday is expected to call for a better 
economic conditions in the light of the increasing impoverishment of 
the underdeveloped world and increased economic cooperation between 
the underdeveloped nations said muchkund dubey permanent secretary 
of economic affairs of the indian foreign ministry 
