kept blacks from succeeding in classical ballet and founded the 
vibrant and youthful company mitchell who retired from the city 
ballet in 1970 has led the troupe to international renown but has 
kept its roots firmly planted in harlem 
the original dance school remains in the primarily black uptown 
manhattan neighborhood and many of this seasons new york 
performances will be held in aaron davis hall at city college 
the dance theater of harlem prides itself on preserving american 
dance repertory and does an excellent job of presenting works that 
otherwise would disappear because they are not performed the 
company also demonstrates a variety of styles and moods from the 
classical swan lake to the neoclassical serenade to the 
contemporary and ethnic dougla to the folk ballet john henry 
last year the troupe captivated audiences in the soviet union 
with its magical retelling of john taras stunning firebird set 
to the original igor stravinsky score 
the companys giselle which had its new york premiere in 
1984 after a london debut is a departure from the traditional work 
set in austria this giselle takes place in louisiana in the 
years following the civil war it is as creole as crawfish and 
gumbo and just as luscious with its mossy sets and pastel costumes 
