<DOCNO> AP890621-0213 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
along louisianas marshy coast its always been 
hard to tell where the land ends and the water begins but the line 
is changing about an acre of rich marshland sinks under water every 
15 minutes and the problem isnt confined to louisiana as reported 
in the first story of a twopart series disappearing wetlands 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
from california to the rocky coast of maine 
whats left of the nations wetlands and barrier islands is 
disappearing nowhere is it going faster than in louisiana where 30 
to 50 square miles of marshy coastline wash away every year 
shrimp fishermen pull trawls over the port eads schoolyard where 
clive duet 73 used to play water 4 feet deep covers the 160acre 
farm near galliano where joe billiot 51 lived as a child 
a 200yearold oak tree stands dying on land near theriot bought 
in 1840 by the greatgrandfather of marvin marmande jr salt water 
once more than a quartermile off has eaten away the marshes and 
now soaks the trees roots 
louisiana with 40 percent of the nations remaining coastal 
wetlands suffers 80 percent of the annual loss its fragile marshes 
are the nurturing grounds for a yearly seafood harvest worth almost 
1 billion the habitat for 40 percent of the countrys furbearing 
animals and the wintering home for nearly 5 million migratory birds 
about half of louisanas marshes have disappeared since world war 
ii wiped out by such natural forces as hurricanes and by levees and 
dams 
in alaska the nations worst oil spill has devastated long 
stretches of coastline but the alaskan wetlands however damaged 
remain eventually they will renew themselves the louisiana 
marshes are gone quietly without drama without nightly newscasts 
without crowds of volunteers 
robert e stewart jr director of the national wetlands research 
center in slidell an arm of the us fish and wildlife service 
said people in europe when ive had the occasion to speak over 
there have said the united states is the most developed the most 
forwardlooking the brightest country in the world how could you 
let this happen 
the simple truth is that we didnt know 40 years ago that it 
was going to happen a lot of the things that started this occurred 
40 years ago and we didnt have the ability to forecast the 
effects 
dave carney a biologist with the army corps of engineers said 
it was only recently that the corps began considering the 
environment as important as flood control and navigation 
in addition carney said it wasnt until 1969 that the 
national environmental policy act imposed a system for rigorous 
environmental examination of federal projects and activities 
many decisions were made long before that tremendous 
investments the whole mississippi river tributaries project all of 
the oil and gas exploration and investment that are now regulated 
were not regulated to that degree back in the 1940s and 1950s when 
these things started popping 
im not saying all of those decisions are irreversible but 
many of them are irreversible commitments of resources and 
decisions made in louisiana before the implications were ever 
imagined 
the scope of the problem is enormous for one thing louisianas 
400milelong coast translates to almost 7000 miles of shore when 
the dips juts and loops of bays inlets and peninsulas are 
included for another the biblical separation of earth and water 
never quite took hold in coastal louisiana and solid objects tend 
to sink in the marshes that merge with the gulf of mexico 
i cannot find any coastal marsh loss rate higher than that of 
louisiana anywhere stewart said but he also emphasized the 
problem was not confined to louisiana 
the united states has lost about 54 percent of its wetlands 
since settlement he said there have also been great losses in 
the dakotas california has lost 90 percent of its wetlands 
you see the same thing in texas mobile bay tampa bay go 
around the florida coast and you see the same thing the florida 
everglades are undergoing tremendous change largely because of 
human impact 
georgia and the carolinas the same sort of thing but to a 
lesser degree its really a more stable coastline so you dont 
have the subsidence you have here you have losses in chesapeake 
bay the net is a loss in all of those areas 
the decisions that affected louisiana were made with clear logic 
and compelling motives but no consideration of longrange harm 
a strong young nation tamed its biggest river system with dams 
and levees first making it a reliable transportation artery then 
keeping it from overflowing nobody pondered how the marshes would 
live without replenishment from siltladen fresh water 
a vigorous oil industry moved into louisianas marshes and the 
gulf of mexico 50 years ago dredging canals to get drilling rigs to 
the oil and to lay pipe to offshore fields nobody considered the 
effects of saltwater canals through freshwater marshes 
and when 27 sets of locks and dams were built on the mississippi 
and the missouri and a giant irrigation project was built far to the 
north in the dakota badlands nobody thought of the louisiana 
marshes 
each one of these dams is a sediment trap stewart said 
they have reduced the sediment substantially in a freeflowing 
system there was up to 500 million tons a year 
it took 700 years for mississippi river sediment to build the 
marshes of the current delta 
it took 22 years from 1956 to 1978 for half of those marshes 
more than 1000 square miles to disappear 
we took a very dynamic system and made it stable stewart 
said and there were some totally unforeseen consequences 
natural forces were at work too spongy soil compresses under 
its own weight salt water levels are rising slowly and hurricanes 
can wipe out miles of marshes in a day 
you take one like betsy in 1965 and it just rolls the marsh up 
like a rug stewart said 
hurricanes pile up walls of water in front of them those tidal 
surges used to dissipate over miles of marshes now they funnel 
through canals and navigation channels spreading salt water miles 
inland killing vegetation and carving up the wetlands 
environmentalists blame big oil and the corps of engineers 
it comes with the territory carney said of the criticism 
in a way the buck does stop here people can study it talk about 
it but eventually anything that is going to be done will be done by 
the state and the corps of engineers in some cooperative way 
h leighton steward chairman chief executive officer and 
president of louisiana land and exploration co says the oil 
industry has been unfairly targeted 
llampe which owns more than 600000 acres of marshland the 
largest private holding of coastal wetlands in the united states 
makes most of its money from oil and gas on its land but also 
leases tracts for hunting and trapping 
steward estimated that hunting for petroleum in the marshes and 
dredging canals to reach oil and gas deposits caused about 10 
percent of the loss 
the remaining 90 percent has been due to natural forces 
exacerbated by the trapping of the mississippi in its current 
channel steward said 
we dont claim we are absolutely guiltless steward said 
because when you build a canal through wetlands you are going to 
chew up a certain amount of wetlands 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

