<TEXT>
it took 700 years for the mississippi river to 
build the marshes near its mouth but half of them have disappeared 
in the last 30 years is there any way to stop the loss any way to 
restore whats gone this second segment in a series disappearing 
wetlands considers what can be done 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the mississippi river built louisianas 
wetlands and only the mississippi can restore them 
louisiana loses an acre of its productive wetlands every 15 
minutes at that rate washington dc would be swallowed up in 
about 14 months 
an estimated 10 percent to 20 percent of louisianas loss is due 
to exploration drilling and production of oil and gas in the 
marshes and offshore the main reason for the rest of the loss is 
that man in taming the mississippi with dams and levees cut off 
the supply of fresh water and silt that kept the wetlands green and 
growing 
any plans for rebuilding marshes involve getting mississippi 
river water back where it used to flow naturally but that calls for 
bigticket items the army corps of engineers is committed to 
spending 130 million for just three freshwater diversion projects 
one under construction at caernarvon about 15 miles downriver from 
new orleans the others in final planning stages 
this is an impoverished state with no money to spare its 
teachers are among the nations lowest paid its police and fire 
departments are cut back to the bone its roads are crumbling and 
its universities are underfunded unemployment is at 117 percent 
the cheaper less dramatic route would be to save whats left if 
possible or delay its loss there are plenty of proposals from 
planting trees to tearing down the levees 
the us soil conservation service is testing marsh grass and 
mangroves to find the toughest strains to help defeat wave action 
and tie down fragile soil 
state and federal agencies are issuing fewer permits for wetlands 
activities 
some ideas seem too small to have any impact bill good and vance 
edwards spread discarded christmas trees in shallow coastal waters 
henry j rodriguez jr plants trees on marshland hummocks roland 
thomas sets out sprigs of marsh grass piles of old christmas trees 
might trap sediment and slow erosion restoring and protecting the 
marsh roots from new vegetation might also hold sediment 
usually thinking big is the way to go but we may have to 
think small on this problem said dave carney of the army corps of 
engineers the first biologist to be named manager of a wetlands 
restoration project by the corps 
louisiana land and exploration co thinks small in a big way 
400 watercontrol weirs on the 600000plus acres it owns in the 
coastal marshes the land the largest private holding of coastal 
wetlands in the country is dotted with llampes oil wells 
starting in 1956 long before the plight of the wetlands was 
obvious llampe began building weirs across inlets and bayous that ebb 
and flow with the tides the low dams their tops below water level 
are designed to break the force of waves on their way in and slow 
their retreat until they have dropped their load of sediment 
the weirs effects have never been scientifically measured but 
comparisons with unprotected marshes show they work asserts h 
leighton steward chief executive officer and president of llampe 
if there are two little natural channels going back into the 
marsh both about 30 feet wide and you put a little weir on one and 
not on the other we can see that after a time one is still 30 feet 
wide and the other has eroded on back into the marshes steward 
said 
we have areas where we have the weirs in place and another 
land owner maybe a mile over has never had them and our guys can 
demonstrate that our land is in better shape than theirs is he 
said 
dag nummendal of louisiana state universitys geology department 
believes such efforts are a losing fight and the focus should be on 
cutting losses rather than spending billions of dollars trying to 
win 
he advocates a retreat from everything south of highway 90 the 
old eastwest route along a natural ridge from new orleans down 
through morgan city then up to lafayette and westward to lake 
charles 
the louisiana geological survey estimates highway 90 will be an 
oceanfront road by 2083 if nothing is done to reverse coastal 
erosion 
nummendal recommends a rearguard action of weirs pumps and dams 
anything to slow the creeping sea while the residents of three 
dozen coastal communities head for higher ground over the next 50 
years 
thats ludicrous thats too ridiculous even to consider 
said marvin marmande jr a houma businessman and farmer to leave 
would mean abandoning land his frenchborn greatgrandfather bought 
in 1840 i would be abandoning everything my father my 
grandfather and my greatgrandfather worked for if i left 
carney and his fellow project manager at the corps of engineers 
jay warren say rudimentary studies have looked at turning the river 
loose below new orleans 
one proposal involved dredging a new navigation channel to 
connect with the mississippi river gulf outlet canal tearing down 
levees and taking ship traffic out of the mississippi 
essentially it would abandon navigation in the mississippi 
river channel let the channel silt up to whatever depth it wanted 
to about 17 feet and put a lock in the river warren said 
the gulf outlet canal is an underused backdoor path from the gulf 
of mexico to new orleans deemed an economic godsend when it was 
dredged through the marshes 30 years ago a major source of flooding 
in hurricane betsy in 1965 it introduced salt water into previously 
fresh marshes in st bernard parish helping to accelerate the death 
of miles of cypress swamps 
manny fernandez spokesman for gov buddy roemer on environmental 
matters said letting the mississippi go wild below new orleans was 
not realistic 
there are tremendous downsides to that fernandez said no 
1 is the cost no 2 is that youre going through a tremendous 
amount of wetlands doing that excavation of a new channel 
growing up in st bernard parish and seeing the tremendous loss 
and devastation from the gulf outlet i dont believe we ought to be 
looking at dredging another channel to solve environmental 
problems 
carney favors building big sluices to let controlled amounts of 
river water flow through the levees and dump replenishing sediment 
through the marshes the freshwater diversion project at caernarvon 
when completed in two years will dump 8000 cubic feet of water 
into the marshes each second 
fernandez said he and the head of the state department of 
environmental quality paul templet believe freshwater and sediment 
diversion structures hold the answer to restoring the marshes 
paul templet has said we may need as many as 20 of these 
structures rather than the one being built and the two or three 
being contemplated fernandez said it will take that many to 
get the silt back in the marshes 
