<TEXT>
while the arguments rage onshore the death toll mounts at sea 
stymied by vast distances and stormy weather bird rescuers have 
been able to capture clean and release only about 500 sea birds 
for every surviving bird more than 50 dead ones lie in freezer vans 
more than 26000 in all and thats just a fraction of total 
mortality some biologists say that for every dead bird collected 
perhaps 100 have died unnoticed 
sea otters appear to be the hardesthit marine mammal the 784 
dead sea otters collected so far represent about onetenth of prince 
william sounds total population harbor seals may be suffering 
too but few carcasses have been found dead seals sink like lead 
balloons explains state marine biologist kathy frost 
the oils lethal reach extends down the food chain on some 
beaches mats of oil have wiped out all life suffocating intertidal 
creatures such as limpets mussels crabs and starfish 
and the oil reaches upward to the tops of tall shoreside spruce 
trees where bald eagles roost oiled sea birds have become a fatal 
attraction for scavenging eagles killing 57 of the birds of prey 
biologists have collected lifeless eggs from 30 abandoned eagle 
nests in the spill area 
hungry brown bears on the shores of katmai national park have 
feasted on oily bird carcasses until they could eat no more digging 
holes in the sand to cache the leftovers 
bears are hardy creatures but biologists have radiocollared 30 
of them to study their reaction to swallowing so much oil we 
havent determined what effect it has on them but i can imagine 
what it would do to me says katmai national park superintendent 
ray bane 
at the very top of the food chain are the humans who live close 
to nature in coastal villages when aleut natives complained that 
the oil spill kept them from gathering food through fishing and 
sealhunting exxon flew in cases of beef chicken and diced ham it 
gave the villagers stomachaches 
many commercial fishermen have been idled by the spill though 
some have landed jobs with exxon leasing their boats at rates of 
3400 a day and more 
most of the salmon and halibut swimming beneath the oil appear to 
be surviving but fisheries worth more than 110 million have been 
canceled or postponed by alaska officials worried that surface oil 
might taint fish as they are hauled from the water in fishermens 
nets 
as spring turns to summer even exxon officials are starting to 
waver on the question of finishing the cleanup by midseptember a 
deadline long dismissed as unrealistic by some state and federal 
officials 
its always a hope says exxons plante but its tougher 
to predict whether well do it by then thats our plan weve 
always said we will not leave it uncleaned and if that means coming 
back so be it 
the sooner the better for all concerned particularly for 120 
frisky sea otters now swimming restlessly in floating pens theyve 
beaten the odds thanks to rescuers at an otter hospital in seward 
the animals are clean healthy and ready to return to the wild 
but they must stay put biologists say because the wild is not 
ready for them 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
david foster is the ap northwest regional 
reporter based in seattle 
