<TEXT>
the rhetoric surrounding the nations 
worst oil spill sometimes has grown as muddled as the north slope 
crude fouling alaskas southern coast 
just how bad is the spill how is the cleanup going heres a 
look at three months of changing pronouncements promises and 
predictions offered by exxon and other officials 
march 24 the exxon valdez rams a reef spilling nearly 11 
million gallons of oil 
march 25 state environmental officials call the initial 
response by exxon and alyeska pipeline service co inadequate and 
unacceptable alyeska spokesman chuck odonnel says i think our 
people did an excellent job the slick covers 28 square miles 
march 30 were going to pick up one way or the other all 
the oil thats out there exxon spokesman don cornett tells 
reporters in valdez 
march 31 the slick now covers 600 square miles absolutely 
not it has not gotten away from us cornett says we are making 
good progress on this cleanup 
april 18 oil has killed at least 1850 birds and 328 sea 
otters the slick has spread over 3000 square miles exxon chairman 
lg rawl says hes confident most beaches will be clean by 
midseptember 
now im not going to tell you that if you go up there a year 
from now you wont find some black places on some rocks but were 
going to make every effort to get it off rawl says 
may 2 in alaska exxon officials say they now plan to leave 
nearly 200 miles of oiled coastline to be cleaned by nature in 
houston exxon president william d stevens says i believe we in 
exxon have shown our commitment and our determination to deal 
responsibly with the spill and all its effects 
oil shows up in katmai national park 300 miles from where the 
tanker grounded 
may 5 exxon spokesman joe tucker says cleanup is progressing 
on schedule oil is sighted 450 miles from where the tanker 
grounded 
may 9 coast guard vice adm clyde robbins says exxon is as 
concerned with public relations as with cleaning up oil they have 
sent pr people into the field instead of operators he says 
may 10 exxon president stevens tells a congressional committee 
the company fully expects to clean up by midseptember the 
wildlife death toll climbs to 9900 birds and 613 sea otters 
may 24 i dont think that we would portray to you that were 
going to take every stain out of all the rocks that are out there 
says exxon official otto harrison in valdez nor do i want to 
portray to you that i think thats necessary to be environmentally 
clean 
june 1 coast guard commandant adm paul yost says he sees 
progress but predicts that exxon almost certainly will miss its 
midseptember deadline i think there was too much optimism he 
says i think reality has set in 
june 14 exxon officials hedge on their september deadline 
its always a hope says exxon spokesman amos plante in seward 
but its tougher to predict whether well do it by then thats 
our plan weve always said we will not leave it uncleaned and if 
that means coming back so be it 
