<TEXT>
a former new york federal reserve bank board 
member pleaded guilty wednesday to illegally passing on confidential 
interest rate data in the first insider trading case involving 
government securities 
in a plea agreement robert a rough 50 pleaded guilty to a 
single bank fraud charge and the government in exchange dropped two 
insider trading charges and four related counts 
rough admitted leaking confidential data while he served as a new 
york fed board member from 1982 to 1984 to a securities firm that 
made about 50 million from the information 
as part of the plea deal prosecutors also agreed to recommend a 
prison term of under one year for the former banker rough faces a 
maximum five years in jail and 10000 fine sentencing is set for 
aug 18 
roughs attorney michael himmel said his client had sent 
letters of apology to the new york fed and federal reserve bank in 
washington 
to me its certainly a step in the right direction an example 
of contrition himmel said 
us district judge dickinson r debevoise called the apologies a 
good step 
rough admitted giving a livingston brokerage confidential data 
about the discount rate set by the fed in washington the new york 
fed and 11 sister regional banks make regular recommendations to the 
fed on the rate which has a powerful bearing on government 
securities 
rough sat on the new york feds board as president of the 
national bank of sussex county in branchville he admitted leaking 
recommendations as well as advance word of a change in the feds 
discount rate 
the allegations surfaced during the 1987 trial of a gilbert c 
schulman president of the brokerage firm of bevill bresler amp 
schulman inc he and three other bevill bresler officials were 
imprisoned for the firms 144 million collapse in 1985 
rough admitted that he passed on the data to schulman a longtime 
friend and business associate and other principals 
the government said the information allowed the firm to make an 
estimated 50 million in profits and avoid losses in exchange 
rough allegedly received 47000 in interest deferred loans 
after the charges were disclosed the fed tightened its 
procedures regarding the discount rate 
himmel said roughs disclosures were not done out of any 
motivation for greed or to line his pockets and blamed pumping 
and prodding by gilbert schulman 
he claimed rough probably would have received the loans from 
bevill bresler regardless of whether he provided the information 
schulman had agreed to cooperate in the prosecution of rough 
himmel said rough a former chairman of the new jersey bankers 
association admitted the facts outlined in those charges even 
though he was not required to plead guilty to them 
in pretrial arguments himmel argued the discount rate data had 
no inherent material value and was not comparable to information 
about stocks but debevoise disagreed ruling that insider trading 
laws could apply to roughs case 
the insider trading charges would have carried a fine of 100000 
per count 
